Description: Very small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a slightly concave area with the impression of wood, probably from a bolt or a box knob, perpendicular to this one impression of a cord with a width of approximately 0.20 cm. The front side is flat with finger impressions and shows part of an oval seal with a circumferential line. The motif shows a cartouche in the middle with a Mn-[khpr-]R' a possible Dd-pillar to the left and another sign (bird?) to the right, the rest is broken off.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
